 2,310 (2016-17)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nces.ed.gov/ccd/schoolsearch/school_detail.asp?Search=1&DistrictID=1201740&ID=120174004445|title=BARTRAM TRAIL HIGH SCHOOL|publisher=National Center for Education Statistics|accessdate=February 3, 2019}}</ref>\n|grades            = [[Ninth grade|9]] - [[Twelfth grade|12]]<ref name=Bartram2 />\n|campus_size       = {{convert|120|acre|km2}}<ref name=Build1>{{cite web |url=http://www.arcadis-us.com/Service+Types/Buildings/Institutional+municipal+government/Projects/Bartram+Trail+High+School.htm |title=Bartram Trail High School |accessdate=2008-03-04 |publisher=www.arcadis-us.com |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061105153525/http://www.arcadis-us.com/Service+Types/Buildings/Institutional+municipal+government/Projects/Bartram+Trail+High+School.htm |archivedate=2006-11-05 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|campus type       = [[Rural]]<ref name=Digger>{{cite web |url=http://www.schooldigger.com/go/FL/schools/0174004445/school.aspx |title=Summary: Bartram Trail High School |accessdate=2008-03-09 |year=2007 |publisher=School Digger |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080516040943/http://www.schooldigger.com/go/FL/schools/0174004445/school.aspx |archivedate=2008-05-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n|nickname          = [[Bear]]s<ref name=Bartram1>{{cite web |url= http://www.staugustine.com/stories/042702/edu_633642.shtml |title= Bartram compiles impressive record in short time |accessdate= 2008-03-03 |last= Grand |first= Ashley |author2= Goncalves, Michelle |year= 2001 |publisher= St. Augustine Record |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110525084425/http://www.staugustine.com/stories/042702/edu_633642.shtml |archive-date= 2011-05-25 |url-status= dead }}</ref>\n|school_colours    = Blue <span style=\"color:blue;\"></span>, Silver <span style=\"color:silver;\"></span> & Black <ref name=Bartram1 />\n|established       = 2000<ref name=Bartram1 />\n|status            = Open\n|homepage          = http://www-bths.stjohns.k12.fl.us/\n}}\n\n'''Bartram Trail High School''' ('''BTHS''') is a [[public school (government funded)|public]] [[high school]] in the [[St. Johns County School District]], located in northwest [[St. Johns County, Florida|St. Johns County]], [[Florida]] ([[United States|U.S.]]) that opened in 2000.<ref name=Bartram1 /> The school was ranked number 327 by ''[[Newsweek]]'' magazine in the top 1,300 high schools in the United States in 2008.<ref name=Newsweek2008>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.newsweek.com/id/39380/?q=2008/rank/301/ |title=\"The Top of the Class\" (2008 list of top high schools) |accessdate=2008-06-11 |year=2008 |magazine=[[Newsweek]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080531143024/http://www.newsweek.com/id/39380/?q=2008%2Frank%2F301%2F |archivedate=2008-05-31 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Academics==\nBartram Trail's curriculum offers many options for students in order to receive a [[high school diploma]]. It includes: [[Art education|art classes]], [[English studies]] and [[English literature|literature]], [[mathematics]], [[performing arts]], [[physical education class]]es, various [[science]] and [[social studies]] classes, [[Vocational education|vocational classes]], [[language education|world and foreign language classes]], [[television]] [[filmmaking#Production|production]], [[musical ensemble|band]], [[Choir|chorus]] and [[turf management]].<ref name=BTHSPro>{{cite web |url= http://www-bths.stjohns.k12.fl.us/academics/Departments/ |title= List of departments on the Bartram Trail High School website |accessdate= 2008-03-04 |publisher= bths.stjohns.k12.fl.us |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20081003092702/http://www-bths.stjohns.k12.fl.us/academics/Departments/ |archive-date= 2008-10-03 |url-status= dead }}</ref>\n\nBartram Trail offers the  [[Air Force Reserve Officer Training Corps]](AFJROTC) Academy which teaches various academic studies along with character and life skills education based around the heritage and traditions of the [[United States Air Force]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.stjohns.k12.fl.us/academies/airforcerotc |title= Air Force JROTC- Bartram Trail High School: Program Description |accessdate= 2008-03-04 |publisher= www.stjohns.k12.fl.us |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080225152008/http://www.stjohns.k12.fl.us/academies/airforcerotc |archivedate= 25 February 2008 |url-status= dead }}</ref> The Bartram Trail High School Academy of Design and Building Construction is available to teach [[carpentry]] and in other fields such as [[interior design]], [[technical drawing|drafting]] and [[fashion design]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.stjohns.k12.fl.us/academies/construction/ |title= Bartram Trail High School Academy of Design and Building Construction: Academy Description |accessdate= 2008-03-04 |publisher= www.stjohns.k12.fl.us |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090306052527/http://www.stjohns.k12.fl.us/academies/construction/ |archive-date= 2009-03-06 |url-status= dead }}</ref> In 2007, Bartram Trail teamed with [[VyStar Credit Union]] to form the Bartram Trail High School VyStar Academy of Business and Finance. The course teaches career opportunities with [[financial services]] and [[management|business management]] industries.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.stjohns.k12.fl.us/academies/finance/ |title= Bartram Trail High School VyStar Academy of Business and Finance: Academy Description |accessdate= 2008-03-04 |publisher= www.stjohns.k12.fl.us |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20090306051828/http://www.stjohns.k12.fl.us/academies/finance/ |archive-date= 2009-03-06 |url-status= dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.firstcoastnews.com/news/news-article.aspx?storyid=92531 |archive-url= https://archive.today/20130123211239/http://www.firstcoastnews.com/news/news-article.aspx?storyid=92531 |url-status= dead |archive-date= 2013-01-23 |title= Students Run Bank at Bartram Trail |accessdate= 2008-03-04 |last= Weeder |first= Roger |year= 2007 |publisher= [[WTLV|First Coast News]] }}</ref> For students with disabilities, the Exceptional Student Education (ESE) program is available.<ref name=PDFBT /><ref name=BTHSPro /> One of the school's newest additions is the [[Information technology|Information Technology]] Academy (IT). The IT academy provides students with foundational technological skills and knowledge that will prepare them for future careers in Information Technology.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www-bths.stjohns.k12.fl.us/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/2016-2017-BTHS-Course-Catalog.pdf|title=BTHS Course Catalog 2016-2017|access-date=2016-10-06|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315174256/http://www-bths.stjohns.k12.fl.us/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/2016-2017-BTHS-Course-Catalog.pdf|archive-date=2016-03-15|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe Advanced Scholars Program at Bartram Trail gives advanced students the opportunity to participate in [[Advanced Placement Program|advanced placement]], [[dual enrollment]] and [[Honors course|honors]] courses in preparation for college.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.stjohns.k12.fl.us/academies/scholars/Bartram%20Trail%20ASP.pdf |title= Bartram Trail High School Advanced Scholars Program |accessdate= 2008-03-04 |publisher= www.stjohns.k12.fl.us |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110727050640/http://www.stjohns.k12.fl.us/academies/scholars/Bartram%20Trail%20ASP.pdf |archive-date= 2011-07-27 |url-status= dead }}</ref> In May 2007, over 1,450 advanced placement exams were given with a passing rate of 54%.<ref name=PDFBT />\n\nThe 2006-2007 school year saw 64% of the students who took the [[Florida Comprehensive Assessment Test]] (FCAT) score the necessary 3 or above in the reading portion of the test and 89% score above the mark on the mathematics section. The FCAT Writing scores saw 92% of the students scoring a 3.5 or above.<ref name=PDFBT />\n\nBartram Trail can give the graduating seniors a choice of [[scholarship]]s they can apply for, through the school, to get started with [[college]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www-bths.stjohns.k12.fl.us/academics/CollegeScholarships/ |title= Scholarship Information for Seniors |accessdate= 2008-03-04 |publisher= bths.stjohns.k12.fl.us |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080309104346/http://www-bths.stjohns.k12.fl.us/academics/collegescholarships/ |archivedate= 9 March 2008 |url-status= dead }}</ref> In 2006, seven Bartram Trail students earned scholarships when they became finalists in the [[National Merit Scholarship Program]].<ref>[http://www.jacksonville.com/tu-online/stories/030306/nes_21241160.shtml Florida Times-Union: Mar 3, 2006- this merits some applause]</ref> The 2006-2007 school year graduation rate was 87.1% with only a 1.0% [[dropping out|drop out]] rate.<ref name=PDFBT />\n\n==History==\nBartram Trail High School was founded in 2000 and was named after the William Bartram Scenic Highway and [[Bartram Trail]] exploration route in the Northern [[St. Johns County, Florida|St. Johns County]] area, and not after [[William Bartram]] himself.<ref name=Bartram1 /><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.jacksonville.com/tu-online/stories/052299/ner_m1newhig.html |title= St. Johns names schools |accessdate= 2008-03-03 |last= Maraghy |first= Mary |year= 1999 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160303234942/http://www.jacksonville.com/tu-online/stories/052299/ner_m1newhig.html |archive-date= 2016-03-03 |url-status= dead }}</ref> Bartram Trail and [[Pedro Menendez High School]] were constructed to relieve [[Human overpopulation|overcrowding]] at [[Allen D. Nease Senior High School]] and [[St. Augustine High School (St. Augustine, Florida)|St. Augustine High School]].<ref name=Bartram1 /> Bartram Trail and Pedro Menendez were the first new high schools built in the [[List of high schools in Florida#St. Johns County|St. Johns County School District]] in twenty years, since Nease was opened in 1981.<ref name=Schools>{{cite web |url= http://www.stjohns.k12.fl.us/schools/#high |title= St. Johns County: High Schools |accessdate= 2008-03-14 |publisher= St. Johns Country School District| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080305175122/http://www.stjohns.k12.fl.us/schools/| archivedate= 5 March 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> However, as the second school year at Bartram Trail began, the original capacity of 1,500<ref name=Campus2>{{cite web |url= http://www.redorbit.com/news/education/271007/bartram_trail_expansion_planned_9thgrade_center_will_help_relieve_school/ |title= Bartram Trail Expansion Planned 9th-Grade Center Will Help Relieve School That is 1,000 Students Overpopulated. |accessdate= 2008-03-07 |date= October 15, 2005 |publisher= Florida Times Union |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522052007/http://www.redorbit.com/news/education/271007/bartram_trail_expansion_planned_9thgrade_center_will_help_relieve_school/ |archivedate=2011-05-22}}</ref> was exceeded with an enrollment of 1,529.<ref name=FTU082901>{{cite web |url= http://www.jacksonville.com/tu-online/stories/082901/ner_7049665.shtml|title= \"Elementary school celebrates anniversary\" on First Coast Community|access-date= 2001-08-29 |year= 2001}}</ref> By the 2002 school year, enrollment was at 1,840, more than 300 students above capacity.<ref name=Digger /> \nIn 2004, the school district projected Bartram Trail's 2007-2008 enrollment at over 3,000.<ref>Miller, Lisa: [http://staugustine.com/stories/120804/new_2751417.shtml \"School district plans for growth includes two new high schools in north\"] St. Augustine Record, December 8, 2004</ref>\n\nTo reduce overcrowding at Bartram Trail and Nease High School, two new high schools, [[Ponte Vedra High School]] and [[Creekside High School (Florida)|Creekside High School]], were constructed and opened for the 2008-2009 school year.<ref name=Schools2>{{cite web |url= http://www.stjohns.k12.fl.us/admin/supt/SWR%2012-17-07.pdf |title= Superintendent's Weekly Review |accessdate= 2008-03-14 |date= December 17, 2007 |publisher= St. Johns Country School District}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2002 to 2006, the Florida Department of Education graded Bartram Trail as an \"A\" school, but in 2007, it was changed to a \"B\" school.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://schoolgrades.fldoe.org/default.asp?action=verifySelectionSchool&report=RC&districts=55&schoolYear=2006-2007%2C+2005-2006%2C+2004-2005%2C+2003-2004%2C+2002-2003%2C+2001-2002%2C+2000-2001&school_grade=&level=School&schoolNumbers=550411 |title= \"School Accountability Reports\" at schoolgrades.fldoe.org |accessdate= 2008-03-28 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110716131423/http://schoolgrades.fldoe.org/default.asp?action=verifySelectionSchool&report=RC&districts=55&schoolYear=2006-2007,+2005-2006,+2004-2005,+2003-2004,+2002-2003,+2001-2002,+2000-2001&school_grade=&level=School&schoolNumbers=550411 |archivedate= 2011-07-16 |url-status= dead }}</ref> Bartram Trail is also named in ''[[Newsweek]]'''s annual list of the top 1,300 high schools in the United States. In 2005, Bartram Trail ranked 894,<ref>{{cite magazine |url= http://www.newsweek.com/id/39380/?sort=Rank&count=1043&Search=&start=800&limit=100&year=2005& |archive-url= https://archive.today/20120907140645/http://www.newsweek.com/id/39380/?sort=Rank&count=1043&Search=&start=800&limit=100&year=2005& |url-status= dead |archive-date= 2012-09-07 |title= \"The Top of the Class\" (2005 list of top high schools) |accessdate= 2008-03-04 |year= 2005 |magazine= [[Newsweek]]}} </ref> in 2006 it was ranked 579,<ref>{{cite magazine |url= http://www.newsweek.com/id/39380/?sort=Rank&count=1236&Search=&start=500&limit=100&year=2006& |archive-url= https://archive.today/20120905022142/http://www.newsweek.com/id/39380/?sort=Rank&count=1236&Search=&start=500&limit=100&year=2006& |url-status= dead |archive-date= 2012-09-05 |title= \"The Top of the Class\" (2006 list of top high schools) |accessdate= 2008-03-04 |year= 2006 |magazine= [[Newsweek]]}} </ref> in 2007 it was ranked 474,<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.newsweek.com/id/39380/?sort=Rank&count=1351&Search=&start=400&limit=100&year=2007& |title=\"The Top of the Class\" (2007 list of top high schools) |accessdate=2008-03-04 |year=2007 |magazine=[[Newsweek]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080204064419/http://www.newsweek.com/id/39380/?sort=Rank&count=1351&Search=&start=400&limit=100&year=2007& |archivedate=2008-02-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and in 2008 it was ranked 327.<ref name=Newsweek2008 />\n\n===\"Victory V\" statue===\nFollowing the [[September 11, 2001 attacks]], the Young Republicans Club<ref name=Statue1>{{cite news |url= http://www.jacksonville.com/tu-online/stories/091202/met_10426827.html |title= St. Johns high school unveils unique sculpture for 9/11 |accessdate= 2008-03-05 |last= Scanlan |first= Dan |date= September 12, 2002 |newspaper= Florida Times-Union}}</ref> at Bartram Trail wanted to get a piece of the destroyed [[World Trade Center (1973-2001)|World Trade Center]] for a memorial to those who died in the attacks.<ref name=Statue2>{{cite web |url= http://staugustine.com/stories/060402/new_759797.shtml |title= Memorial to WTC victims at Bartram |accessdate= 2008-03-05 |last= Brown |first= August |date= June 4, 2002 |publisher= St. Augustine Record}}</ref> Students sent letters to the Office of Emergency Management in [[New York (state)|New York]], forwarded by the former principal, Jim Springfield.<ref name=\"Statue2\"/> The office replied in May 2002 and agreed to let them own a piece of the World Trade Center debris as long as Springfield came to [[New York City]] and got it himself. He received the debris on May 21, 2002; the piece was a six-foot-long piece of [[I-beam]] [[steel]] that weighed seven hundred [[pound (mass)|pounds]].<ref name=Statue1 /><ref name=Statue2 />\n\nThe concept behind the sculpture, created by art teacher Robert Kirk,<ref name=Statue1 /> was that the piece of World Trade Center debris was to be one-half of the letter \"V\" while the other half was to be made of pristine [[stainless steel]].<ref name=Statue2 /> The \"V\" was to stand for \"Victory\", and was to [[symbol]]ize the \"somber tragedy and the unity of [[United States|American]] resolve.\"<ref name=Statue2 /> The sculpture was unveiled in Bartram Trail's courtyard on September 11, 2002, one year after the attacks, with [[List of Governors of Florida|Florida Governor]] [[Jeb Bush]] attending the ceremony.<ref name=Statue1 /> Only seventy-three pieces of World Trade Center debris were donated, and it is believed that this was the only piece in Florida<ref name=Statue1 /> and the only piece in an American high school.<ref name=Statue2 />\n\n===Super Bowl XXXIX===\nFor [[Super Bowl XXXIX]], in 2005, Bartram Trail High School was selected by the [[National Football League]] as the practice facility for [[AFC Championship Game|AFC champion]] [[New England Patriots]].<ref name=SuperBowl>{{cite web |url= http://www.firstcoastnews.com/news/news-article.aspx?storyid=20857 |archive-url= https://archive.today/20130123235452/http://www.firstcoastnews.com/news/news-article.aspx?storyid=20857 |url-status= dead |archive-date= January 23, 2013 |title= St. Johns County School To Host Super Bowl Participant |accessdate= 2008-03-07 |date= July 2, 2004 |publisher= [[WTLV|First Coast News]] }}</ref><ref name=SuperBowl2>{{cite news |url= http://www.jacksonville.com/tu-online/stories/110204/hig_17077729.shtml |title= Bartram Trail reaps dividend from NFL investment |accessdate= 2008-03-07 |last= Goodbread |first= Chase |date= November 2, 2004 |newspaper= Florida Times-Union}}</ref> Bartram Trail was selected by the NFL because the [[World Golf Hall of Fame|World Golf Village]] was chosen as the New England Patriots lodging and the practice field had to be within twenty minutes of their hotel. Bartram Trail was also selected because the school's location was remote with little traffic and interference and because the walk from the lockers to the field was short enough.<ref name=SuperBowl2 /> Bartram Trail was the first high school ever that was chosen to be the practice facility for a [[Super Bowl]] team.<ref name=SuperBowl4>{{cite web |url= http://staugustine.com/stories/013005/new_2857697.shtml |title= Bartram Trail set to host Patriots |accessdate= 2008-03-07 |last= Barney |first= Justin |date= January 1, 2005 |publisher= St. Augustine Record}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Bartram Trail field.jpg|thumb|300px|right|The Bartram Trail High School football field that was redone by the [[National Football League]].]]\n\nThe NFL made modifications to Bartram Trail, installing new lockers, making a new practice field and modifying their game field to professional standards.<ref name=SuperBowl /> The field modifications, however, were delayed by [[Hurricane Frances]] and caused them to start over several times.<ref name=SuperBowl2 /> Bartram Trail's field was considered one of the top five high school fields in Florida, but the problem was that the field was supported by dirt, instead of sand.<ref name=SuperBowl5>{{cite web |url= http://www.staugustine.com/stories/012905/new_2850132.shtml |title= Meticulous care secret to Bartram Trail's super field |accessdate= 2008-03-07 |last= Rodgers |first= Diane |date= January 29, 2005 |publisher= St. Augustine Record |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110525082339/http://www.staugustine.com/stories/012905/new_2850132.shtml |archive-date= May 25, 2011 |url-status= dead }}</ref> To fix this, the NFL modified Bartram Trail's football field by building the fields up with two hundred loads of sand, adding a drainage system and building the slope, crown and type of grass to the same specifications as [[Jacksonville Municipal Stadium]].<ref name=SuperBowl5 /> Students from the Bartram Trail [[turf management]] classes worked with [[George Toma]], who had built all thirty-nine fields for the Super Bowl games,<ref name=SuperBowl5 /> in building and maintaining the field.<ref name=SuperBowl4 />\n\nAfter the two weeks of practice in Bartram Trail, a few of the New England Patriots and owner [[Robert Kraft]] came in on the last day to talk with the students and thank them for their hospitality, as New England head coach [[Bill Belichick]] had done earlier in a morning press conference.<ref name=SuperBowl3>{{cite news |url= http://www.boston.com/sports/football/patriots/articles/2005/02/05/grass_gets_greener/ |title= Grass gets greener |accessdate= 2008-03-07 |last= Cafardo |authorlink=Nick Cafardo|first= Nick |date= February 5, 2005 |newspaper= The Boston Globe}}</ref>\n\n===Project Alaska Turf===\nIn February 2007, Project Alaska Turf was started by Cathy Parker, a Bartram Trail High School parent and wife of a Bartram Trail football offensive coordinator.<ref name=Alaska1>{{cite web |url= http://www.projectalaskaturf.com/ |title= Project Alaska home page |accessdate= 2008-03-08 |year= 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080223102848/http://www.projectalaskaturf.com/| archivedate= 23 February 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref><ref name=Alaska3>{{cite web |url= http://staugustine.com/stories/030107/news_4436227.shtml |title= Bartram to provide Barrow turf field |accessdate= 2008-03-08 |last=Carlyon |first=Hays |date= March 1, 2007 |publisher= St. Augustine Record}}</ref><ref name=Alaska8>{{cite web |url= http://www.firstcoastnews.com/news/spotlight/news-article.aspx?storyid=89942 |title= First Coast Makes Frozen Football Dream Come True |accessdate= 2008-03-08 |last= Kamm |first= Grayson |date= August 27, 2007 |publisher= [[WTLV|First Coast News]] }}{{Dead link|date=June 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Project Alaska Turf was inspired by an [[Emmy Award]] winning [[ESPN]] documentary by Wayne Drehs on a community in [[Utqiagvik, Alaska]]. The documentary focused on a football program that was implemented in order to reverse high [[teenage suicide]] rates, accelerated [[dropping out|drop out]] rates and increased teen [[drug abuse]].<ref name=Alaska1 /> Project Alaska Turf was funded by Bartram Trail, the [[Jacksonville Jaguars]], ProGrass and the Grimes Companies.<ref name=Alaska5 /> The project was aimed at raising money to provide a football team, the Barrow Whalers, an artificial turf field to replace their gravel-covered field.<ref name=Alaska1 /> Since Utqiagvik (formerly known as Barrow), Alaska is above the [[Arctic Circle]], grass doesn't grow there, resulting in their football field being made of dirt and gravel and causing injury to the players.<ref name=Alaska5>{{cite news |url= http://www.jacksonville.com/tu-online/stories/030107/hig_8307313.shtml |title= Field goal: Raise $500,000 to fund tundra turf |accessdate= 2008-03-08 |last=Schneider |first= Jason |date= March 1, 2007 |newspaper= Florida Times-Union| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080307073832/http://www.jacksonville.com/tu-online/stories/030107/hig_8307313.shtml| archivedate= 7 March 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Barrow-Whalers-turf-field.jpg|thumb|250px|left|Side view of the Barrow Whalers' new turf field in [[Utqiagvik, Alaska]].]]\n\nThe original goal was to raise $500,000 to make the field,<ref name=Alaska2>{{cite news |url= http://dwb.adn.com/sports/prep/football/story/8656163p-8547110c.html |title= Barrow football could receive artificial-turf |accessdate= 2008-03-08 |last= Demarban |first= Alex |date= February 20, 2007 |newspaper= Anchorage Daily News |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080918102747/http://dwb.adn.com/sports/prep/football/story/8656163p-8547110c.html |archive-date= September 18, 2008 |url-status= dead |df= mdy-all }}</ref> but the ending target was eventually set to $800,000.<ref name=Alaska6>{{cite web |url= http://staugustine.com/stories/081907/news_4784007.shtml |title= Miracle in Barrow |accessdate= 2008-03-08 |last=Schneider |first= Jason |date= August 19, 2007 |publisher= St. Augustine Record}}</ref> The money covered the cost of buying, shipping and installing all one hundred and sixty tons of turf.<ref name=Alaska2 />\n\nThe Barrow Whalers were invited to Florida on May 17 through the May 19<ref name=Alaska5 /> but the Whalers didn't arrive until June.<ref name=Alaska6 /> Restaurateurs and other business owners provided them free room and board upon their arrival.<ref name=Alaska2 /> During their visit to Jacksonville, they scrimmaged against another local team<ref name=Alaska4>{{cite web |url= http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/news/story?id=2772290 |title= Alaska team has friends in warm places |accessdate= 2008-03-08 |last=Drehs |first=Wayne |date= February 20, 2007 |publisher= [[ESPN]]}}</ref> and toured [[Jacksonville Municipal Stadium]], where the Jacksonville Jaguars play.<ref name=Alaska6 />\n\nThe field was completed with $700,000 generated from the donation; $100,000 short of the goal.<ref name=Alaska8 /> The Bartram Trail community worked for a long period of time and managed to move the field from Florida to Alaska by trucks, boats, trains, and on airplanes with help from ten different companies.<ref name=Alaska7>{{cite news |url= http://www.jacksonville.com/tu-online/stories/082707/met_194916917.shtml |title= Jacksonville woman helps Alaskans score pretty touchdown |accessdate= 2008-03-08 |last=Hall |first=Brendan |date= August 27, 2007 |newspaper= Florida Times-Union| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080205021520/http://www.jacksonville.com/tu-online/stories/082707/met_194916917.shtml| archivedate= 5 February 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> The field was opened in time for the Barrow Whalers first game on August 17, 2007, which they won, 18-16, after being down by two [[touchdown]]s with three minutes left in the game.<ref name=Alaska1 /> The game was the first live internet broadcast of a sporting event in the United States from north of the Arctic Circle<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web |url= http://www.republicanherald.com/site/news.cfm?newsid=18697246&BRD=2626&PAG=461&dept_id=529073&rfi=6 |title= Broadcast to make history |accessdate= 2008-03-14 |last=Souders |first=Chuck |date= August 14, 2007 |publisher= [[Republican & Herald]]}}</ref> and had [[NBC]], [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]], [[ESPN]], and most of Alaska's media there to cover the event.<ref name=Alaska6 />\n\n===Controversies===\nOver Bartram Trail's brief history, there have been multiple [[bomb threat]]s and a threat of a [[school shooting]].\n\nOn October 16, 2001, at about 2:20&nbsp;p.m.,<ref name=Bomb1>{{cite web |url= http://www.staugustine.com/stories/110802/new_1110729.shtml |title= 3 Bartram students arrested |accessdate= 2008-03-06 |last= Walters |first= Ron |date= November 8, 2002 |publisher= St. Augustine Record |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110525082417/http://www.staugustine.com/stories/110802/new_1110729.shtml |archive-date= May 25, 2011 |url-status= dead }}</ref> the school was under \"code green\" as a dark bag with the word \"bomb\" was found in the hallways on the second floor.<ref name=Bomb2>{{cite web |url= http://216.116.225.75/stories/101701/new_220574.shtml |title= Anxious moments |accessdate= 2008-03-06 |last= Lewis |first= Ken |date= October 17, 2001 |publisher= St. Augustine Record }}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Authorities [[emergency evacuation|evacuated]] the school and kept everyone at least five hundred feet away. Near 5 p.m., the bomb squad had removed the bag out of the school with a long rope and drove away with it.<ref name=Bomb2 /> The bag only contained stuffed recycled paper and a two-liter bottle with more recycled paper sticking out of it.<ref name=Bomb1 /> Seven students were arrested in connection to the incident. Four had their charges dismissed while one boy [[plea]]ded [[guilt (law)|guilty]] to writing the note and was [[sentence (law)|sentence]]d to [[probation]] and [[community service]].<ref name=Bomb1 />\n\n[[File:Bartram Trail High.jpg|thumb|350px|right|The west entrance into Bartram Trail High School.]]\n\nOn November 6, 2002, three female students of Bartram Trail were arrested and charged for \"a false report of bombing or [[arson]] against state-owned property\", a second-degree [[felony]].<ref name=Bomb1 /><ref name=Bomb4>{{cite news |url= http://www.clickondetroit.com/news/1774264/detail.html |title= Girls Charged In Bomb Threat Ordered Held For 21 Days |accessdate= 2008-03-06 |date= November 8, 2002 |newspaper= Detroit News |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110609043802/http://www.clickondetroit.com/news/1774264/detail.html |archivedate=2011-06-09}}</ref> The threat was written on the partition between bathroom stalls,<ref name=Bomb1 /> reported as saying something akin to \"This school will be blown to bits at noon\".<ref name=Bomb3>{{cite web |url= http://www.staugustine.com/stories/012403/new_1278701.shtml |title= Bomb threat clears out Landrum Middle School |accessdate= 2008-03-06 |last= Noonan |first= Bryan |date= January 24, 2003 |publisher= St. Augustine Record |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110525082435/http://www.staugustine.com/stories/012403/new_1278701.shtml |archive-date= May 25, 2011 |url-status= dead }}</ref> The threat was specific for noon on November 5, 2002.\n\nDuring the time of the threat, the school was evacuated and searched by deputies and [[police dog|explosives detection dogs]], but nothing was found.<ref name=Bomb1 /> Two of the students were arrested at Bartram Trail on November 6, and the third was arrested at their home.<ref name=Bomb1 /> The Youth Resource Deputy had received anonymous tips and learned that they talked about the threat, wrote about it on the bathroom wall and got rid of the marker they had used.<ref name=Bomb1 /> The students were sentenced to twenty-one days at a [[youth detention center]] while evaluations took place and after they were released they had to remain under [[curfew]] and other restrictions until the case was finished.<ref name=Bomb4 /> It concluded with the students having to \"reimburse the county and the sheriff's office for the expense of the deployment.\"<ref name=Bomb3 />\n\nOn April 18, 2007, the St. Johns County Sheriff's Office arrested a fourteen-year-old student of Bartram Trail after he had posted an [[e-mail]] to a friend stating he wanted to conduct a mass [[school shooting]].<ref name=Shooting1>{{cite web |url= http://www.news4jax.com/news/12445023/detail.html |title= Bartram Trail Student Accused Of Making Mass Shooting Threat |accessdate= 2008-03-06 |date= April 18, 2007 |publisher= Channel 4 News: Jacksonville |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927151804/http://www.news4jax.com/news/12445023/detail.html |archivedate=2011-09-27}}</ref><ref name=Shooting2>{{cite web |url= http://i.abcnews.com/US/story?id=3056317&page=1 |title= College and School Campuses Throughout the Country Have Received Several Threats |accessdate= 2008-03-06 |date= April 19, 2007 |publisher= [[ABC News]]}}{{dead link|date=July 2013}}</ref><ref name=Shooting3>{{cite news |url= http://www.jacksonville.com/tu-online/stories/042807/nes_165907589.shtml |title= E-threat: In an era of heightened school security, even idle threats can lead to big trouble |accessdate= 2008-03-06 |date= April 28, 2007 |newspaper= The Florida Times-Union}}</ref> The e-mail stated that he planned to top the [[Virginia Tech massacre]] of thirty-three deaths by killing a hundred students.<ref name=Shooting1 /><ref name=Shooting3 /> The threat wasn't directed at Bartram Trail or any other school specifically nor was he in possession of any weapons.<ref name=Shooting3 /> The friend's parent saw the e-mail and reported it.<ref name=Shooting1 /><ref name=Shooting2 /> Authorities checked around the school and didn't find anything suspicious. The student was charged with the \"threat to throw, project, place or discharge any destructive device\", a second degree felony.<ref name=Shooting1 /><ref name=Shooting3 /> The same student had also made threats that were never reported.<ref name=Shooting1 /><ref name=Shooting2 />\n\n==Campus==\n[[File:Bartram Trail campus.PNG|left|thumb|250px|[[Satellite imagery|Satellite image]] of the Bartram Trail High School campus in 2004.]]\nThe land for Bartram Trail High School was purchased in January 1999<ref name=Campus>{{cite web |url= http://www.staugustine.com/stories/080600/new_20000806.002.shtml |title= Bartram Trail: Home of the Bears |accessdate= 2008-03-04 |last= Merlo |first= Tiffany |year= 2000 |publisher= St. Augustine Record |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110525082928/http://www.staugustine.com/stories/080600/new_20000806.002.shtml |archive-date= 2011-05-25 |url-status= dead }}</ref> and was constructed by Arcadis.<ref name=Build1 /> The Bartram Trail High School campus takes up one hundred and twenty [[acre]]s of land and the school building takes up {{convert|190000|sqft|m2}}.<ref name=Build1 /> The school building is a two-story octagon with an open-air [[courtyard]] in the center. The [[cafeteria]] and [[Hybrid library|media center]] are located within the main building, while the [[gymnasium (school)|gymnasium]] and [[auditorium]] with a [[stage (theatre)|stage]] are attached on the south and north sides, respectively.<ref name=Campus /> The outside of the campus has walkways, student, faculty and visitor parking, a parent drop-off section, a bus loop, a football and track [[stadium]], a baseball and softball field, tennis courts, general-use play fields, a stormwater treatment facility, water and sewer utilities and a wetland mitigation area.<ref name=Build1 />\n\n===Extensions===\nThe Bartram Trail school building was originally designed to hold 1,500 students, but enrollment for the 2005-2006 school year exceeded 2,500.<ref name=Campus2 /> To provide classrooms needed immediately,  [[portable building]]s were set up on the east side of the campus. The number of portable buildings used by year is, as follows:<ref name=FTU092507>{{cite news |url=http://www.jacksonville.com/tu-online/stories/092507/met_202690700.shtml |last=Perhach |first=Paulette |title=St. Johns public schools continue fast enrollment growth |accessdate=2008-03-23 |date=September 25, 2007 |newspaper=Florida Times-Union |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110812131828/http://jacksonville.com/tu-online/stories/092507/met_202690700.shtml |archivedate=2011-08-12 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.jacksonville.com/tu-online/stories/082003/nes_13309227.shtml|title= Bartram Trail overcrowding becoming hot topic in PTO |accessdate= 2003-08-20 |year= 2003 |newspaper= Florida Times-Union}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.jacksonville.com/tu-online/stories/082005/nep_19541810.shtml|title= Portables doing their job to help school crunch |accessdate= 2005-08-20 |year= 2005 |newspaper= Florida Times-Union}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.jacksonville.com/tu-online/stories/080702/ner_10101306.shtml|title= Schools ready for crowds in early start |accessdate= 2002-08-07 |year= 2002 |newspaper= Florida Times-Union}}</ref>\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin: 1em auto 1em auto\"\n|+ \n! 2002-03 || 2003-04 || 2004-05 || 2005-06 || 2006-07 || 2007\u20132008\n|-\n|  <center>10</center>  ||  <center>25</center>  ||  <center>42</center>  ||  <center>55</center>  ||  <center>56</center>  || <center>36</center>\n|}\n</center>\n\nAdditionally, for the 2007-2008 school year, a new permanent structure was built and opened at the northeast corner of the school to house the Ninth Grade Center.<ref name=Campus2 /><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.bsi.fsu.edu/0708_sip_template/cprint.aspx?id=1254 |title= School Improvement Plan: Bartram Trail High School |accessdate= 2008-03-09 |year= 2007 |publisher= Florida Department of Education }}{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> With the opening of [[Creekside High School (Florida)|Creekside High School]] for the 2008-2009 school year, enrollment fell below capacity. The portables were no longer needed and were removed at the end of the 2007-2008 school year.\n\n==Athletics==\nBartram Trail has a variety of athletics programs, which is supervised by [[athletic director]], Ben Windle.<ref name=Athletics>{{cite web |url= http://www-bths.stjohns.k12.fl.us/athletics/ |title= Bartram Trail High School Athletics |accessdate= 2008-03-04 |publisher=bths.stjohns.k12.fl.us| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080311024744/http://www-bths.stjohns.k12.fl.us/athletics/| archivedate= 11 March 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref> Athletics offered at Bartram Trail include:\n\n{|border=0 |\n|valign=top |\n*Varsity and junior varsity [[baseball]]\n*Boys and girls [[basketball]]\n*Varsity and junior varsity [[cheerleading]]\n*Boys and girls [[cross country running|cross country]]\n*[[Dance]]\n*Varsity and junior varsity [[American football|football]]\n*Boys and girls [[golf]]\n*Boys and girls [[lacrosse]]\n|valign=top |\n*Boys and girls varsity [[association football|soccer]]\n*Boys and girls junior varsity soccer\n*Varsity and junior varsity [[softball]]\n*Boys and girls [[Swimming (sport)|swimming]]\n*Boys and girls [[tennis]]\n*Boys and girls [[track and field]]\n*[[Winter guard]]\n*[[Wrestling]]\n|}\n*Boys and girls [[Olympic weightlifting|weightlifting]]\n<center>\n:{| class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\" width=550px\n|+\n! colspan=\"7\" style=\"text-align:center;\" bgcolor=\"\"|<big>'''Championships'''</big>\n|-\n!Sport\n!Year\n!Championship \n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" style=\"vertical-align:top;\"|Baseball<ref name=Baseball>{{cite web |url= http://www-bths.stjohns.k12.fl.us/athletics/baseball/ |title= Baseball department on the Bartram Trail High School website |accessdate= 2008-03-04 |publisher= bths.stjohns.k12.fl.us |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080227064026/http://www-bths.stjohns.k12.fl.us/athletics/Baseball/ |archivedate= 27 February 2008 |