age": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bartram_Trail_High_School"}
{"title_page": "David Bowles (author)", "text_new": "{{short description|American poet, translator and author|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| birth_name = David Oscar Bowles, Jr.\n| image = David Bowles 2018.jpg\n| caption = Bowles at the 2018 Texas Book Festival\n| alt = An image of author David Bowles taken in June of 2016.\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1970|2|27}}\n| birth_place = [[Upper Marlboro, Maryland]], [[United States]]\n| occupation = Poet, novelist, translator\n| notableworks = ''The Smoking Mirror'' <br> ''They Call Me G\u00fcero''\n| awards = [[Belpr\u00e9 Medal|Pura Belpr\u00e9 Author Honor]]; [[Texas Institute of Letters|Texas Institute of Letters Translation Award]]; [[We Need Diverse Books|Walter Dean Myers Honor]]; [[Bank Street College of Education|Claudia Lewis Award for Excellence in Poetry]]; [[Tom\u00e1s Rivera Award|Tom\u00e1s Rivera Mexican American Children\u2019s Book Award]]\n| website = {{url|www.davidbowles.us}}\n}}\n\n'''David Bowles''' (born 1970) is an American poet, translator and author.\n\n==Life and career==\n\nDavid Bowles was born to residents of the [[Rio Grande Valley]] of Texas in 1970. He is of Mexican descent.{{sfn|Bowles on Inclusive Literature}}\n \nMuch of Bowles' work stems from his research into border legends and pre-Columbian Mesoamerican mythology, featured on [[Monsters and Mysteries in America]].{{sfn|Donna Author on National TV}} He is currently developing a TV series based on his book ''Border Lore'' with Mucho M\u00e1s Media and Campanario Entertainment.{{sfn|This Is Horror}}\n\nIn addition, Bowles has translated multiple books, poems and stories from languages as diverse as [[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[Nahuatl]],{{sfn|Flower, Song, Dance}} [[Yucatec Mayan]],{{sfn|Perform with Drums}} and [[Japanese language|Japanese]].{{sfn|Meet David Bowles}} He is also a poet, with two books of verse and poems published widely.{{sfn|Interview with David Bowles}}\n\nBowles also writes speculative fiction,{{sfn|Interview with David Bowles}} such as his MG/YA fantasy series ''Garza Twins'',{{sfn|TSM Postcard}} that features Latino protagonists and Mesoamerican mythology.{{sfn|Bowles on Inclusive Literature}} He worked with [[Adam Gidwitz]] on the ''Unicorn Rescue Society'' series for [[Dutton Penguin]].{{sfn|In the Beginning}} His speculative fiction work includes graphic novels like the steampunk title ''Clockwork Curandera'' he created with illustrator [[Ra\u00fal the Third|Ra\u00fal \"the Third\" Gonz\u00e1lez]].{{sfn|Book Deals}}\n\nBowles resides in [[Donna, Texas]]. Holding a Master's in English and a doctorate in Education, he is a professor in the Department of Literatures & Cultural Studies at the [[University of Texas Rio Grande Valley]], where he teaches children's/adolescent literature and [[Nahuatl]].{{sfn|UTRGV}} {{sfn|Donna Author on National TV}}\n\nIn February 2017, David Bowles was elected to the [[Texas Institute of Letters]].{{sfn|TIL 2017}} In January 2020, he co-founded the hashtag / literary activist campaign [[DignidadLiteraria|#DignidadLiteraria]].\n\n==Awards and honors==\n* ''Flower, Song, Dance: Aztec and Mayan Poetry'': awarded the [[Texas Institute of Letters]]' 2014 Soeurette Diehl Fraser Award for Best Translation.{{sfn|TIL Award List}}\n* TOP SHELF Book Review Column: received a 2014 Texas [[Associated Press]] Managing Editors' Headliners Excellence in Journalism Award for Comment and Criticism.{{sfn|TAPME Award List}}\n* ''The Smoking Mirror'' was selected as a [[Belpr\u00e9 Medal|Pura Belpr\u00e9 Honor Book]] in 2016 by the [[American Library Association]].{{sfn|2016 ALA Winners}}\n* Inducted into the [[Texas Institute of Letters]] in 2017.{{sfn|TIL 2017}}\n*''They Call Me G\u00fcero'' has received multiple accolades: \n**Selected Best Book of 2018 by the [[School Library Journal]]\n**Selected a 2019 Notable Verse Novel by the [[National Council of Teachers of English|NCTE]] Award for Excellence in Children\u2019s Poetry Committee\n**Named one of the 2018 Best Children's & Teen Books of the Year by [[Shelf Awareness]]. \n**2019 Honor Book for the [[We Need Diverse Books|Walter Dean Myers Award for Outstanding Children's Literature]] in the Younger Reader category.\n**2019 [[Belpr\u00e9 Medal|Pura Belpr\u00e9 Honor Book]]\n**2019 [[Bank Street College of Education|Claudia Lewis Award for Excellence in Poetry]]\n**[[Association for Library Service to Children]] Notable Children's Book, 2019\n**2019 [[Tom\u00e1s Rivera Award|Tom\u00e1s Rivera Mexican American Children\u2019s Book Award]] \n**2018 Jean Flynn Award for Best Middle Grade Book from the [[Texas Institute of Letters]]\n**Selected for the 2020-2021 Texas Bluebonnet Award Master List by the [[Texas Library Association]]\n**The [[International Youth Library]] Foundation named it a White Raven, a recommended title for international children\u2019s and youth literature.\n*''Feathered Serpent, Dark Heart of Sky'' received the [[Texas Institute of Letters]] Award for Best Young Adult Book. It was also selected a Best YA Book of 2018 by [[Kirkus Reviews]] and was a [[YALSA Award for Excellence in Nonfiction|YALSA Award Nominee for Excellence in Nonfiction]].\n\n==Works==\nAS AUTHOR\n\n'''Novels'''\n* ''The Chupacabras of the Rio Grande'' (The Unicorn Rescue Society, #4). Co-authored by [[Adam Gidwitz]]. Illustrated by Hatem Aly. New York: [[Dutton Penguin]], 2019.\n* ''Lords of the Earth''. Hobart, Australia: Severed Press, 2016.\n*Garza Twins Series\n** ''The Smoking Mirror'' (#1). Melbourne: [[IFWG Publishing]], 2015.\n** ''A Kingdom Beneath the Waves'' (#2). Melbourne: [[IFWG Publishing]], 2016.\n** ''The Hidden City''. (#3). Melbourne: [[IFWG Publishing]], 2018.\n\n'''Story Collections'''\n* ''Chupacabra Vengeance''. Tigard, Oregon: Broken River Books, 2017.\n* ''The Seed: Stories from the River's Edge''. Spring, TX: Absey & Co., 2011.\n\n'''Graphic Novels'''\n* '''Tales of the Feathered Serpent''' series\n**''Rise of the Halfling King''. Illustrated by Charlene Bowles. El Paso, TX: [[Cinco Puntos Press]], 2020. (Forthcoming.) \n* '''Clockwork Curandera''' series\n** ''Vol. 1\u2014The Witch Owl Parliament''. Illustrated by Ra\u00fal the Third. New York, NY: [[Tu Books]], 2020. (Forthcoming.)\n\n'''Chapter Books'''\n*13th Street Series\n**''Battle of the Bad-Breath Bats'' (#1). New York, NY: HarperChapters, 2020 (Forthcoming).\n**''The Fire-Breathing Ferret Fiasco'' (#2). New York, NY: HarperChapters, 2020 (Forthcoming).\n**''Clash of the Cackling Cougars'' (#3). New York, NY: HarperChapters, 2020 (Forthcoming).\n**''Shocking Shark Showdown'' (#4). New York, NY: HarperChapters, 2020 (Forthcoming).\n\n'''Myth and Legend'''\n* ''Feathered Serpent, Dark Heart of Sky: Myths of Mexico''. El Paso, TX: [[Cinco Puntos Press]], 2018.\n* ''Ghosts of the Rio Grande Valley''. Charleston: [[The History Press]], 2016.\n* ''Border Lore: Folktales and Legends of South Texas''. Beaumont, TX: [[Lamar University|Lamar University Press]], 2015.\n* ''Creature Feature: 13 Frightening Folktales of the Rio Grande Valley''. McAllen, TX: AIM Media Texas, 2013.\n* ''Mexican Bestiary''. Donna, TX: VAO Publishing, 2012.\n\n'''Poetry'''\n* ''They Call Me G\u00fcero: A Border Kid's Poems''. El Paso, TX: [[Cinco Puntos Press]], 2018. \n* ''Shattering and Bricolage''. Dallas, TX: Ink Brush Press, 2014.\n\nAS TRANSLATOR\n* ''The Sea-Ringed World: Sacred Stories of the Americas''. Translation of ''Diccionario de mitos de Am\u00e9rica'' by Mar\u00eda Garc\u00eda Esper\u00f3n. New York, NY: Levine Querido. 2021 (forthcoming).\n* ''Me dicen G\u00fcero: Poemas de un chavo fronterizo''. Translation of ''They Call Me G\u00fcero.'' New York, NY: Vintage Espa\u00f1ol. 2020 (forthcoming).\n* ''Snake Poems: An Aztec Invocation''. Special Edition for Camino Del Sol Series. Nahuatl translation of the original text by [[Francisco X. Alarc\u00f3n]]. Tucson, AZ: [[University of Arizona Press]]. March 12, 2019.\n* ''El verano de las mariposas''. Translation of ''Summer of the Mariposas'' by Guadalupe Garc\u00eda McCall. New York, NY: [[Tu Books]], 2018.\n* ''Flower, Song, Dance: Aztec and Mayan Poetry''. Beaumont, TX: [[Lamar University|Lamar University Press]], 2013.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite web|author=Adam Gidwitz|year=2018|title=In the Beginning Was the Name|url=https://nerdybookclub.wordpress.com/2017/12/14/in-the-beginning-was-the-name-by-adam-gidwitz/|work=Nerdy Book Club|publisher=Nerdy Book Club|accessdate=2018-01-08|ref={{sfnref|In the Beginning}}}}\n* {{cite web |author=Madeline Smither |year=2014 |title=Donna author to talk about 'Big Bird' local legend on national TV |url=http://www.themonitor.com/news/local/article_a66d697c-9455-11e3-b2db-0017a43b2370.html |work=The Monitor |publisher=The Monitor |accessdate=2015-09-06 |ref={{sfnref|Donna Author on National TV}} }}\n* {{cite news |last=Rasmussen |first=Peter |date=July 28, 2015 |title=''The Smoking Mirror'': Stories of Shapeshifting Drive Bowles\u2019 New Novel  |url=http://www.themonitor.com/life/vidaeducation/the-smoking-mirror-stories-of-shapeshifting-drives-bowles-new-novel/article_9fb0c070-353a-11e5-818f-e7e2fb9f8554.html |publisher=The Monitor |accessdate=2015-09-06 |ref={{sfnref|Stories of Shapeshifting}} }}\n* {{cite news |last=Vourvoulias |first=Sabrina |date=April 10, 2015 |title=Meet David Bowles, author of ''The Smoking Mirror'' |url=http://aldianews.com/articles/culture/literature/meet-david-bowles-author-smoking-mirror/38586 |publisher=AL D\u00cdA |accessdate=2015-09-06 |ref={{sfnref|Meet David Bowles}} }}\n* {{cite web |last=Vourvoulias |first=Sabrina |date=June 29, 2015 |title=Introduction to \"Winds that Stir Vermillion Sands\" |url=http://www.strangehorizons.com/2015/20150629/1bowlesintro-f.shtml |publisher=Strange Horizons |accessdate=2015-09-06 |ref={{sfnref|Introduction}} }}\n* {{cite web |last=Fowler |first=Olivia |year=2015 |title=Author Interview: David Bowles on Inclusive Literature, the Hugos, and the Futur